description:
Tick finding via /porting-to-rust differential probe vs vendored replication.c::waitaofCommand.

UPSTREAM (replication.c lines 3579-3582):
  if (numlocal && !server.aof_enabled) {
      addReplyError(c, "WAITAOF cannot be used when numlocal is set but appendonly is disabled.");
      return;
  }

FR CURRENT (crates/fr-command/src/lib.rs::waitaof_cmd lines 7833-7838):
  if required_local > 0 {
      return Ok(RespFrame::Error(
          "ERR WAITAOF cannot be used when numlocal is set but appendonly is disabled."
              .to_string(),
      ));
  }

The fr guard fires unconditionally when numlocal > 0, ignoring the actual aof_enabled state. Upstream only fires this error when AOF is OFF; if AOF is enabled, WAITAOF proceeds (in fr's standalone stub it would short-circuit to [0, 0] just like the numlocal=0 path).

REPRO:
  CONFIG SET appendonly yes
  WAITAOF 1 0 0
    upstream → [0, 0]  (would block in real instance, returns immediately in standalone)
    fr      → 'ERR WAITAOF cannot be used when numlocal is set but appendonly is disabled.'

Severity: [LOW]. Visible to anyone who enables AOF and probes WAITAOF — they get a misleading 'appendonly is disabled' error.

FIX:
  Change the guard to `if required_local > 0 && !store.aof_enabled`. If AOF is on, fall through to the existing [0, 0] return path (no real fsync tracking is wired up — that's a separate stubbed area per project_wait_commands_stub).

REVIEW MODE Tick 14 finding via /mock-code-finder, fifth in the cluster after 8tk8h/ymyrt/2usb3/t344m. fr's MEMORY STATS hardcodes one db.0 entry and zeroes its inner overhead.hashtable.main/expires/slot-to-keys counters, ignoring per-db state across the 16 supported dbs.

LOCATION (crates/fr-command/src/lib.rs lines 15465-15490):
  items.push(RespFrame::BulkString(Some(b'db.0'.to_vec())));
  if store.dispatch_client_ctx.resp_protocol_version == 3 {
      items.push(RespFrame::Map(Some(vec![
          (BulkString('overhead.hashtable.main'), Integer(0)),
          (BulkString('overhead.hashtable.expires'), Integer(0)),
          (BulkString('overhead.hashtable.slot-to-keys'), Integer(0)),
      ])));
  } else { ... flat 6-element Array ... }

UPSTREAM (legacy_redis_code/redis/src/object.c::getMemoryOverheadData line 1300+ + memoryCommand line 1582+):

  for (j = 0; j < server.dbnum; j++) {
      redisDb *db = server.db+j;
      long long keyscount = dictSize(db->dict);
      if (keyscount == 0) continue;   // skip empty dbs

      mh->total_keys += keyscount;
      mh->db[mh->num_dbs].dbid = j;
      mh->db[mh->num_dbs].overhead_ht_main = dictMemUsage(db->dict);
      mh->db[mh->num_dbs].overhead_ht_expires = dictMemUsage(db->expires);
      mh->db[mh->num_dbs].overhead_ht_slot_to_keys = ...;
      mh->num_dbs++;
  }

  // memoryCommand STATS:
  addReplyMapLen(c, 27 + mh->num_dbs);
  ...
  for (j = 0; j < mh->num_dbs; j++) {
      char dbname[32];
      snprintf(dbname, 32, 'db.%ld', mh->db[j].dbid);
      addReplyBulkCString(c, dbname);
      addReplyMapLen(c, 3);
      addReplyBulkCString(c, 'overhead.hashtable.main');
      addReplyLongLong(c, mh->db[j].overhead_ht_main);
      addReplyBulkCString(c, 'overhead.hashtable.expires');
      addReplyLongLong(c, mh->db[j].overhead_ht_expires);
      addReplyBulkCString(c, 'overhead.hashtable.slot-to-keys');
      addReplyLongLong(c, mh->db[j].overhead_ht_slot_to_keys);
  }

So upstream emits one db.<j> entry per NON-EMPTY db, with inner overhead.hashtable.main = dictMemUsage(db->dict) (real bytes, ~64-88 per entry).

DATA AVAILABLE in fr:
  - Store::database_count: usize (=16 by default)
  - Store::dbsize_in_db(db): usize
  - Store::expires_in_db(db): usize

Severity: [LOW]. Affects observability tools when:
  - Server is empty (fr emits db.0 with all zeros; upstream emits no db.<n> at all)
  - Workload uses non-default db (fr always reports db.0 even when keys live in db.5; upstream reports db.5)
  - Multi-db workload (fr only reports db.0; upstream reports all non-empty dbs)

Reproducer:
  redis-cli> SELECT 5
  redis-cli> SET k v
  redis-cli> MEMORY STATS
  upstream: db.5 entry with overhead.hashtable.main:>0
  fr (current): db.0 entry with overhead.hashtable.main:0

Fix:
1. Iterate dbs 0..database_count, emit db.<n> only when dbsize_in_db(n) > 0.
2. Approximate overhead.hashtable.main as dbsize_in_db(n) * 64 (rough dictEntry size; upstream's dictMemUsage returns total bucket+entry memory).
3. Approximate overhead.hashtable.expires as expires_in_db(n) * 64.
4. Keep slot-to-keys at 0 (fr doesn't implement cluster slot-to-key map).
5. Update existing memory_stats_db_sub_map_shape_matches_protocol test to seed a key before asserting db.0 is present.
6. Add new test for multi-db iteration (db.5 present when only db.5 has keys; db.0 absent).

REVIEW MODE Tick 14 finding. Sibling of jnf53. ZPOPMIN/ZPOPMAX without COUNT emits a flat 2-Array (member,score) under both protocols — that matches upstream. But with COUNT, upstream switches to a use_nested_array path under RESP3.

UPSTREAM (legacy_redis_code/redis/src/t_zset.c::zpopMinMaxCommand line 4040):

  long count = -1;
  if (c->argc == 3 && getPositiveLongFromObjectOrReply(c, c->argv[2], &count, NULL) != C_OK)
      return;
  // Respond with a single (flat) array in RESP2 or if count is -1
  // (returning a single element). In RESP3, when count > 0 use nested array.
  int use_nested_array = (c->resp > 2 && count != -1);
  genericZpopCommand(c, &c->argv[1], 1, where, 0, count, use_nested_array, 0, NULL);

  // genericZpopCommand body:
  if (!use_nested_array && !emitkey) {
      addReplyArrayLen(c, rangelen * 2);   // RESP2 flat 2N
  } else if (use_nested_array && !emitkey) {
      addReplyArrayLen(c, rangelen);       // RESP3 outer N
  }
  // per-row:
  if (use_nested_array) addReplyArrayLen(c, 2);  // RESP3 nested 2-Array
  addReplyBulkSds(c, ele);
  addReplyDouble(c, score);

Wire shapes:
  ZPOPMIN k 3 (RESP2): *6 m1 s1 m2 s2 m3 s3
  ZPOPMIN k 3 (RESP3): *3 (*2 m1 s1) (*2 m2 s2) (*2 m3 s3)

FR (crates/fr-command/src/lib.rs zpopmin@4535, zpopmax@4567): both COUNT branches build flat alternating Array regardless of protocol. The no-COUNT branch correctly returns a 2-Array, matching upstream's count==-1 behavior.

ZMPOP / BZPOPMIN / BZPOPMAX checked: ZMPOP always wraps (use_nested_array hardcoded to 1 in upstream and fr does it too). BZPOPMIN/BZPOPMAX flatten unconditionally (key + flat scores) — matches upstream.

Severity: [HIGH]. Same root cause as jnf53 (ZRANGE-family WITHSCORES) but on the ZPOP family. Any RESP3 client (lettuce, jedis 5+, redis-py 5+, ioredis 5+, go-redis v9, redis-rs >= 0.23) calling ZPOPMIN/ZPOPMAX with COUNT after HELLO 3 sees a wire shape that doesn't match the protocol contract.

Reproducer:
  redis-cli -3> ZADD z 1 a 2 b 3 c
  redis-cli -3> ZPOPMIN z 2
  upstream RESP3: *2 (*2 a 1) (*2 b 2)
  fr     RESP3: *4 a 1 b 2

Fix:
1. zpopmin/zpopmax COUNT branches: branch on store.dispatch_client_ctx.resp_protocol_version. Under RESP3, emit Array<[member, score]>; under RESP2, keep flat. The no-COUNT branch is unchanged.
2. Add regression test covering both RESP3 nested + RESP2 flat shapes.

/profiling-software-performance follow-up to v1twi:

  pub fn feed_monitors(&mut self, argv: &[Vec<u8>], now_ms: u64, db: usize) {
      ...
      let mut line = format!(\"+{secs}.{usecs:06} [{} 127.0.0.1:0]\", db);
      for arg in argv {
          line.push(' ');
          ...
          for &b in arg.iter() {
              ...
              line.push(b as char);
              ...
          }
      }
      line.push_str(\"\\r\\n\");
      let line_bytes = line.into_bytes();
      for &client_id in &self.server.monitor_clients {
          self.server.monitor_output.push((client_id, line_bytes.clone()));
      }
  }

Two perf wastes:

1. line is String, so every line.push(b as char) pays the char-validation overhead (the byte-to-char cast goes through Rust's char encoding path even for plain ASCII). For each argv byte the loop validates capacity + UTF-8 invariants. The final into_bytes is a wasteful re-walk that the codegen often can't elide.

2. The buffer is Vec<u8>-shaped on the consuming side (monitor_output stores Vec<u8>) — converting to/from String at the boundary buys nothing semantically.

Fix: switch the local 'line' to Vec<u8>. format!() once, then write! / extend_from_slice / push(b) — write! works on Vec<u8> via std::io::Write. Skips the UTF-8 invariant check entirely on every printable byte. line.into_bytes() becomes a no-op (plain `let line_bytes = line;`).

Same hot path matters for MONITOR streams over binary payloads (RDB chunks, MIGRATE dumps) — every connected MONITOR client gets a clone() of the line bytes per propagated command.

REVIEW MODE finding (cross-cutting consequence of i40x2-family RESP3 Map shape).

Source: crates/fr-runtime/src/lib.rs:6781-6803

  let current_config =
      self.handle_config_get(&[b'CONFIG'.to_vec(), b'GET'.to_vec(), b'*'.to_vec()]);
  if let RespFrame::Array(Some(pairs)) = current_config {
      for chunk in pairs.chunks(2) {
          if let (RespFrame::BulkString(Some(k)), RespFrame::BulkString(Some(v))) =
              (&chunk[0], &chunk[1])
          {
              ...
              lines.push(format!('{key} {val}'));
          }
      }
  }
  let content = lines.join('\\n') + '\\n';
  // ...write content to config file...

handle_config_get at lib.rs:6892 already correctly emits RespFrame::Map under RESP3:

  if self.session.resp_protocol_version == 3 {
      ...
      return RespFrame::Map(Some(pairs));
  }
  RespFrame::Array(Some(entries))

So when CONFIG REWRITE is issued under a HELLO 3 session, the internal CONFIG GET * call returns Map. The if-let RespFrame::Array doesn't match. lines stays empty. content = '\\n'. The config file is OVERWRITTEN with a single blank line — every config directive lost.

Severity: [HIGH]. Silent destructive data loss. A user running 'redis-cli -3 CONFIG REWRITE' (perfectly reasonable) would blank their entire config file. Reachable from any RESP3 client with admin access.

Fix: handle BOTH Array and Map shapes when iterating the internal CONFIG GET reply. The rewriter doesn't actually need the protocol-shaped wire form — it just needs k/v pairs. Either:
(A) match both RespFrame::Array(Some(items)) (chunks of 2) and RespFrame::Map(Some(pairs)) (already pairs);
(B) stop using the wire-shaping handler internally and call collect_config_entries directly to get the flat entries vec.

(A) is the smaller, safer change. Going with that.

# RDB Decoder Fuzz Test

## What
A property-based test that feeds corrupted RDB data to decode_rdb() and verifies it returns Err, never panics.

## Why
RDB files could be corrupted by disk errors, truncation, or adversarial tampering. The decoder must handle ALL corrupted inputs gracefully without panicking.

## Implementation
1. Add proptest as a dev-dependency to fr-persist
2. Strategy 1 — Random mutation:
   ```rust
   proptest! {
       #[test]
       fn decode_rdb_never_panics_on_mutation(seed_entries: Vec<u8>, flip_idx: usize, flip_bit: u8) {
           let valid = encode_rdb(&[...standard entries...], &[]);
           let mut corrupted = valid.clone();
           if flip_idx < corrupted.len() {
               corrupted[flip_idx] ^= flip_bit;
           }
           let _ = decode_rdb(&corrupted); // Ok or Err, never panic
       }
   }
   ```
3. Strategy 2 — Truncation at every byte:
   ```rust
   #[test]
   fn decode_rdb_handles_truncation_at_every_offset() {
       let valid = encode_rdb(&[...entries...], &[]);
       for i in 0..valid.len() {
           let _ = decode_rdb(&valid[..i]); // must not panic
       }
   }
   ```
4. Strategy 3 — Completely random bytes:
   ```rust
   proptest! {
       #[test]
       fn decode_rdb_never_panics_on_random(data: Vec<u8>) {
           let _ = decode_rdb(&data);
       }
   }
   ```
5. Fix any panics found

## Files
- crates/fr-persist/Cargo.toml (add proptest dev-dependency)
- crates/fr-persist/src/lib.rs (add proptest tests)

