DEBUG SDSLEN <key> returns either:
  - 'ERR no such key'                      if key doesn't exist
  - 'ERR Not an sds encoded string.'       if value is int-encoded or non-string
  - +SimpleString with 6 sds-state fields  for embstr/raw strings

fr-command's debug_cmd at crates/fr-command/src/lib.rs:17072 doesn't recognize SDSLEN — it falls through to the catch-all 'ERR unknown subcommand or wrong number of arguments for SDSLEN. Try DEBUG HELP.' branch, breaking tooling that probes string layout via SDSLEN.

fr stores keys/values as Vec<u8> rather than upstream's sds buffer, so the avail/zmalloc fields can't carry their original meaning. We surface the closest synthetic equivalents: key_sds_len = key.len(), key_sds_avail = 0, key_zmalloc = key.len(), and same for val_*. Tooling that parses the format gets a syntactically valid reply; tools that depend on the exact numbers would already be unreliable across allocators.

Acceptance:
- DEBUG SDSLEN missing → +ERR no such key
- DEBUG SDSLEN list_key → +ERR Not an sds encoded string.
- DEBUG SDSLEN int_key (canonical i64 string)  → +ERR Not an sds encoded string.
- DEBUG SDSLEN string_key → +SimpleString matching upstream format
- Wrong-arity → unknown-subcommand error shape (matches existing siblings)
- Tests stay green; clippy clean.

REVIEW MODE finding (Tick 14, REVIEW-MODE.md cycle). Fresh-eyes pass on fr-command/src/lib.rs latency_cmd HISTOGRAM branch (lines 17103-17146).

UPSTREAM (legacy_redis_code/redis/src/latency.c lines 463-695):

  // latencyCommand HISTOGRAM (no args): outer Map of cmd_name → CDF
  void *replylen = addReplyDeferredLen(c);
  latencyAllCommandsFillCDF(c, server.commands, &command_with_data);
  setDeferredMapLen(c, replylen, command_with_data);

  // latencyAllCommandsFillCDF body (called per command):
  addReplyBulkCBuffer(c, cmd->fullname, ...);   // outer Map key
  fillCommandCDF(c, cmd->latency_histogram);    // outer Map value

  // fillCommandCDF (the inner CDF):
  addReplyMapLen(c, 2);                          // 2-entry Map
  addReplyBulkCString(c, 'calls');               // key 1
  addReplyLongLong(c, total_count);              // value 1
  addReplyBulkCString(c, 'histogram_usec');      // key 2
  void *replylen = addReplyDeferredLen(c);
  // ... iterate buckets, emit (bucket_us, cumulative_count) pairs ...
  setDeferredMapLen(c, replylen, samples);       // value 2 = Map of bucket_us → count

So upstream wire shape is, under RESP3:
  Map { cmd_name: Map { 'calls': count, 'histogram_usec': Map { bucket_us: count, ... } } }
And under RESP2 (alternating-Array form):
  Array [ cmd_name, Array [ 'calls', count, 'histogram_usec', Array [ bucket_us, count, ... ] ], cmd_name, Array [...] ]

FR (crates/fr-command/src/lib.rs:17125-17146):

  let result: Vec<RespFrame> = histograms.into_iter().map(|(cmd, hist)| {
      let mut map_items = vec![
          BulkString('calls'), Integer(hist.calls),
      ];
      for (bucket_start_us, count) in hist.to_buckets() {
          map_items.push(Integer(bucket_start_us));
          map_items.push(Integer(count));
      }
      Array([BulkString(cmd_name), Array(map_items)])  // 2-tuple wrapper!
  }).collect();
  Ok(Array(result))

Two distinct shape divergences:

  (1) Outer envelope. fr emits N elements where each is a 2-element Array [cmd_name, hist]. Upstream emits 2N alternating elements [cmd_name, hist, cmd_name, hist, ...] under RESP2 / Map<cmd_name → hist> under RESP3. fr's nested-tuple form does not match either upstream shape, regardless of protocol.

  (2) Inner histogram. fr emits 'calls', count, bucket_us, count, bucket_us, count, ... (single flat array, no histogram_usec separator). Upstream emits a 2-entry Map: { 'calls': count, 'histogram_usec': <Map of buckets> }. fr is missing the histogram_usec key entirely AND inlining bucket pairs at the same level as calls.

Severity: [HIGH]. Wire-format on a real LATENCY subcommand that observability tools (RedisInsight, datadog-redis-integration, prometheus_redis_exporter) parse to graph per-command CDFs.

Existing test latency_histogram_returns_recorded_data (line 34438) asserts the bug — it pins the [name, flat_array] tuple shape and the inlined-bucket inner shape. Test must be updated alongside the fix.

Reproducer:
  redis-cli> CONFIG SET latency-tracking yes
  redis-cli> GET nonexistent
  redis-cli> LATENCY HISTOGRAM GET
  RESP2 expected: GET\r\n*4 calls 1 histogram_usec *2 64 1
  RESP2 actual:   *1 ( *2 GET *4 calls 1 64 1 )

Fix plan:
1. latency_cmd HISTOGRAM branch: emit 2-pair inner Map { calls, histogram_usec } where histogram_usec value is itself a Map (RESP3) / flat-Array (RESP2) of bucket_us → count
2. Outer envelope: emit Map<cmd_name → inner> under RESP3, flat alternating Array under RESP2
3. Update latency_histogram_returns_recorded_data to match upstream RESP2 shape; add new RESP3 test pinning Map shape.

Per /vibing-with-ntm/REVIEW-MODE.md: ship the fix in this same tick.

Differential probe vs upstream Redis 7.2.4 replication.c::replicaofCommand:3137-3196. Upstream's pre-conditions before applying REPLICAOF:

  if (server.cluster_enabled) {
      addReplyError(c,'REPLICAOF not allowed in cluster mode.');
      return;
  }
  if (server.failover_state != NO_FAILOVER) {
      addReplyError(c,'REPLICAOF not allowed while failing over.');
      return;
  }
  // ... NO ONE special case ...
  if (c->flags & CLIENT_SLAVE) {
      addReplyError(c, 'Command is not valid when client is a replica.');
      return;
  }
  // ... port validation ...

fr-runtime's handle_replicaof_command at crates/fr-runtime/src/lib.rs:11303-11354 has none of these. It accepts NO ONE / host port unconditionally and toggles role/backlog state, even when cluster mode is enabled or the issuing client is itself a connected replica.

Concrete repros:
  > CONFIG SET cluster-enabled yes  (or start with --cluster-enabled yes)
  > REPLICAOF 127.0.0.1 6380
  fr returns:  +OK   (and reconfigures replication despite cluster mode)
  upstream:    (error) ERR REPLICAOF not allowed in cluster mode.

  > (PSYNC handshake completes — this connection is now a replica)
  > REPLICAOF 127.0.0.1 6381
  fr returns:  +OK   (replica reconfigures itself, racing with master's flush)
  upstream:    (error) ERR Command is not valid when client is a replica.

