REVIEW MODE finding (cross-review of peer commit a14597a / bw15):

The new coroutine implementation uses a sentinel error string to signal yield from inside a coroutine body:

  const LUA_YIELD_SENTINEL: &str = '__frankenredis_lua_coroutine_yield__';
  fn is_lua_yield_signal(err: &str) -> bool { err == LUA_YIELD_SENTINEL }

  'coroutine.yield' => {
      if self.current_coroutine.is_some() {
          self.pending_yield = Some(args.to_vec());
          Err(LUA_YIELD_SENTINEL.to_string())
      } else {
          Err('attempt to yield across metamethod/C-call boundary'.to_string())
      }
  }

The sentinel is detected with a plain string match (lua_eval.rs:2493 in exec_coroutine_stmts and 2910/2926 in pcall/xpcall):

  Err(err) if is_lua_yield_signal(&err) => {
      let values = self.pending_yield.take().unwrap_or_default();
      return Ok(CoroutineRun::Yield { values, next_pc: offset + 1 });
  }

But the 'error' Lua builtin (line 2881-2887) returns Err(user-supplied message) directly:

  'error' => {
      let msg = args.first().map(|a| a.to_display_string()).unwrap_or_default();
      Err(String::from_utf8_lossy(&msg).to_string())
  }

So a user script can forge the sentinel:

  local co = coroutine.create(function()
      error('__frankenredis_lua_coroutine_yield__')
  end)
  local ok, val = coroutine.resume(co)
  -- ok = true, val = nil (spoofed yield with empty values)

The exec_coroutine_stmts arm takes pending_yield via .take().unwrap_or_default() — when pending_yield is None (because coroutine.yield was NOT called), it falls through to Vec::new(), and the resume returns (true, ...) as if a real yield happened.

Severity: [LOW] — observable behavior bug, not a sandbox escape. The spoofed yield only affects the script's own coroutine state and pcall/xpcall returns. No host-side impact. But it diverges from upstream Lua / Redis: upstream's error() raises an actual error that pcall catches; there is no way for a script to simulate yield without calling coroutine.yield.

Fix: gate the sentinel detection on `self.pending_yield.is_some()`. If the script forged the sentinel via error(), pending_yield is None → fall through to the regular Err arm → coroutine.resume sees the user error string. If coroutine.yield was actually called, pending_yield is Some → real yield path.

