Store::list_fits_legacy_listpack_size at crates/fr-store/src/lib.rs:1967-1981 walks the full list to accumulate `value.len() + 11` bytes against max_bytes, even when the running total has already crossed the budget. For a 1M-element list, every OBJECT ENCODING call iterates all 1M elements regardless of where the threshold blows.

  let total: usize = list.iter().map(|v| v.len() + 11).sum();
  total <= max_bytes

Fix: short-circuit on accumulator overflow. Same arithmetic, lower constant factor:

  let mut total: usize = 0;
  for v in list {
      total = total.saturating_add(v.len() + 11);
      if total > max_bytes { return false; }
  }
  true

OBJECT ENCODING isn't on the hottest path, but it's called by INFO scrapers, observability tools, and DEBUG OBJECT — bounded-iteration is the upstream behavior (t_list.c::listTypeTryConversion bails at the first overflow per element-add, not after walking the whole list).

Acceptance: behavior unchanged for the listpack case; large quicklist payloads return after at most O(max_bytes / min_value_size) steps instead of O(N).

[LOW] severity — not a correctness bug, a constant-factor cleanup. Useful for shops scraping OBJECT ENCODING for memory-saturation alarms.

