  // Inside single-quoted token: same rule.

So upstream requires a closing quote to be followed by whitespace OR end-of-input. fr silently splits inputs like SET key "hello"world into [SET, key, hello, world] instead of erroring with the 'unbalanced quotes' message.

Severity: [MEDIUM]. Wire-format conformance + security-adjacent: a client building inline commands by concatenation could inject extra args via key"payload"trailer if trailer isn't whitespace. Upstream rejects outright. fr accepts and splits.

Reproducer:
  split_inline_args(b'SET key "hello"world')
  upstream: Err
  fr (current): Ok([b'SET', b'key', b'hello', b'world'])

Fix:
1. After consuming the closing quote, check that the next byte (if any) is whitespace. If not, return the same Protocol-error-unbalanced-quotes error.
2. Same fix for single-quoted branch.
3. Add regression test asserting both forms are rejected.
4. Ensure normal cases (SET key value, no-trailer-after-close-quote) still parse.

REVIEW MODE finding (cross-review of peer commit a14597a / bw15):

The new resume_coroutine + exec_coroutine_stmts tracks next_pc at the OUTER statement level only:

  for (offset, stmt) in stmts.iter().enumerate().skip(start_pc) {
      ...
      Err(err) if is_lua_yield_signal(&err) && self.pending_yield.is_some() => {
          let values = self.pending_yield.take().unwrap_or_default();
          return Ok(CoroutineRun::Yield {
              values,
              next_pc: offset + 1,        // ← only advances past the outer stmt
          });
      }

So a yield from inside a for-loop / while / repeat / if-block / function call propagates up through the inner exec_stmts, and the outer iteration captures next_pc = (outer-stmt-index + 1). On resume, the outer for-loop is SKIPPED entirely instead of resuming at the next iteration.

Verified with this script:

  local co = coroutine.create(function()
      for i = 1, 3 do
          coroutine.yield(i)
      end
  end)
  local _, v1 = coroutine.resume(co)  -- 1st resume: yields 1
  local _, v2 = coroutine.resume(co)  -- 2nd resume: completes early
  local _, v3 = coroutine.resume(co)
  return {v1, v2, v3}

Expected (upstream Lua 5.1): {1, 2, 3}
Actual (fr):                  {1}             ← v2 + v3 are nil; loop iterations 2/3 were dropped

Same pattern breaks: yield inside while / repeat / if / function call.

Severity: [MEDIUM] — substantial behavioral divergence on a common Lua coroutine pattern. Real coroutine workloads (streaming iterators, multi-stage script generators) would silently produce wrong results.

Proper fix (full step-resumable interpreter) is multi-day scope. Minimal observable-correctness fix in this tick: detect the unsafe case at coroutine.yield time and return an explicit error matching Lua 5.1's wording 'attempt to yield across metamethod/C-call boundary' instead of silently dropping iterations.

Detection: track nested_exec_stmts_depth on LuaState — bump on entering exec_stmts, decrement on exit. coroutine.yield errors if depth > 0 (we're inside a nested block / function call rather than at the coroutine's outer-stmt level).
